# Linux kernel config fragment: Bluetooth — onboard UART (Broadcom) + USB.
#
# CANONICAL COPY. Edit here, then run `make sync` to materialize identical
# copies into each target subdir (rpi3/, rpi4/, ...). The per-target copy is
# what the build references (subdir-local path keeps git `sparse:` consumption
# and artifact checksums correct).
#
# Merged over each target's base defconfig via
# BR2_LINUX_KERNEL_CONFIG_FRAGMENT_FILES. `make olddefconfig` (run by the
# Nerves kernel build) only pulls in symbols reached via `select`, NOT via
# `depends on` — a dependent symbol whose `depends on` prerequisite is unmet
# is silently dropped. So list every `depends on` prerequisite explicitly.
# CONFIG_RFKILL is already in the stock rpi3 base defconfig.
#
# SERIAL_DEV_BUS (+ the ttyport controller) is the serdev core that
# BT_HCIUART_SERDEV `depends on`. Without it the kernel never binds the
# `bluetooth` serdev node under the UART, so no hci0 auto-attaches at boot.
# (Verified on rpi3 hardware: v0.1.0 set BT_HCIUART_SERDEV=y but, lacking
# SERIAL_DEV_BUS, olddefconfig reverted it to n and /sys/bus/serial was absent.)
CONFIG_SERIAL_DEV_BUS=y
CONFIG_SERIAL_DEV_CTRL_TTYPORT=y
CONFIG_BT=y
CONFIG_BT_HCIUART=y
CONFIG_BT_HCIUART_SERDEV=y
CONFIG_BT_HCIUART_BCM=y

# USB Bluetooth adapters (btusb). Separate driver/path from the onboard
# UART chip: btusb auto-probes on USB enumeration (no serdev/attach), so a
# dongle just appears as a new hciN. CONFIG_USB is already on in the base
# defconfig. The chip sub-options below are `default y` under BT_HCIBTUSB,
# but listed explicitly per the select-vs-depends-on note above. NOTE:
# firmware-bearing dongles (Realtek rtl_bt, MediaTek, Intel) still need
# their blobs in /lib/firmware (linux-firmware) — not provided here;
# firmware-free (CSR-style) dongles work with just the driver.
CONFIG_BT_HCIBTUSB=y
CONFIG_BT_HCIBTUSB_BCM=y
CONFIG_BT_HCIBTUSB_RTL=y
CONFIG_BT_HCIBTUSB_MTK=y
